{"timestamp": "2025-12-07 00:49:09.330840", "event": "llm_end", "text": "Troubleshooting Diagnosis Report\n\nScope\n- Detect anomalies, localize faulty devices, and identify likely root causes using current network telemetry (reachability tests, host configs, routing/OSPF state, and service listening sockets).\n\nHigh-level Assessment\n- Core routing/OSPF: Healthy and converged. All core and distribution nodes have consistent OSPF adjacencies and route tables across backbone (area 0) and the distribution area (0.0.0.1). No LSA churn or adjacency drops observed. ECMP appears configured where relevant; metrics are consistent.\n- Server access segment (10.200.0.0/24): Layer-2 bridge and L3 uplink are up. Routes to/from this subnet are present across the fabric. DNS and Apache servers are listening and reachable at L3.\n- End-to-end reachability: Broad ping sampling shows 0% loss across many inter-subnet pairs with typical low latencies; occasional jitter outliers but no systemic loss or asymmetry.\n\nKey Findings and Evidence\n1) Host misconfiguration (access segment 10.2.1.0/24)\n   - host_2_1_1_1 lacks any IP configuration:\n     - ifconfig/ip addr: eth0 up but no inet address; ip route is empty.\n     - get_reachability mapping shows host_2_1_1_1: null IP; ping tests from that host show status \"unknown”.\n   - Expected per design: static IP in 10.2.1.0/24 with default gateway 10.2.1.1.\n   - Localization: Fault isolated to endpoint host_2_1_1_1 itself (not the switch/router), since:\n     - The distribution gateway for that subnet is up and routing: switch_dist_2_1 br0 = 10.2.1.1/24, OSPF routes correct.\n     - Other 10.2.x hosts show normal reachability to various destinations.\n\n2) OSPF and routing state (normal)\n   - router_core_1/2/3 and distribution switches (switch_dist_1_1, switch_dist_2_1) show stable OSPF:\n     - Multiple areas present and consistent; ABRs identified correctly on distribution devices.\n     - All user and server subnets (10.1.x.0/24, 10.2.x.0/24, 10.200.0.0/24) are installed with expected next-hops.\n   - switch_server_access (server farm):\n     - br0 = 10.200.0.1/24, eth5 = 172.16.0.23/31 uplink to router_core_3 (172.16.0.22/31).\n     - OSPF database clean and routes to backbones present.\n\n3) Services status (normal)\n   - DNS server (dns_server 10.200.0.2):\n     - netstat shows named listening on 10.200.0.2:53 and on loopback; default route is via 10.200.0.1.\n     - Ping paths from dns_server to hosts succeed (0% loss) in sampled tests.\n   - Web servers (web_server_0…3 10.200.0.3–.6):\n     - netstat shows 0.0.0.0:80 listening; default route via 10.200.0.1.\n     - Sampled pings between web servers and campus hosts successful.\n\n4) Reachability/jitter observations (informational)\n   - Extensive inter-subnet pings (e.g., to 10.1.2.6 and 10.1.4.8) show 0% loss; RTTs mostly 1–5 ms with some higher outliers (e.g., >10 ms), consistent with lab/container scheduling variance rather than network faults.\n   - No pattern of asymmetry or loss indicating a fabric issue.\n\nAnomalies Detected\n- host_2_1_1_1 is not configured with an IP address (and has no default route), preventing any L3 communication from that host. This is the only clear fault observed.\n\nFault Localization\n- Faulty device: host_2_1_1_1 (access segment 10.2.1.0/24).\n- Surrounding infrastructure (switch_access_2_1_1, switch_dist_2_1, core, and server access) appears healthy and correctly routing.\n\nRoot Cause\n- Endpoint misconfiguration: Missing static IP configuration on host_2_1_1_1 (contrary to the network design where hosts use static addresses in 10.<core>.<dist>.0/24 and default gateway on the distribution switch).", "generation_info": {"finish_reason": "stop", "logprobs": null}, "invalid_tool_calls": [], "usage_metadata": {"input_tokens": 67761, "output_tokens": 3368, "total_tokens": 71129, "input_token_details": {"audio": 0, "cache_read": 0}, "output_token_details": {"audio": 0, "reasoning": 2368}}}
